    • rangeIsProperSubsetOnBothEnds

      public static <C extends java.lang.Comparable<? super C>> boolean rangeIsProperSubsetOnBothEnds​(com.google.common.collect.Range<C> subset, com.google.common.collect.Range<C> superSet)
      Check if the first Range is a "proper" subset of the second. Note that we're interpreting "proper" to mean that there is at least one point on BOTH the upper and lower bounds of the superset that is NOT in the subset.

      Open Ranges (a, b), closed ranged [a, b] and mixed open closed [a, b), (a, b] are supported. (a, b) would be considered a proper subset of [a, b], but (a, b] would not.

      'Unrestricted' ranges, where one bound is +/- infinity, e.g. [a, inf), (-inf, b] are also supported. If both Ranges are unrestricted on the same end, we check the other to see if it qualified as "proper". E.g. we consider [2, inf) to be a proper subset of [1, inf).

    • rangeIsSafelyProperSubsetOf

      public static <T extends RBNumeric<? super T>> boolean rangeIsSafelyProperSubsetOf​(com.google.common.collect.Range<T> subset, com.google.common.collect.Range<T> superSet, Epsilon epsilon)
      Tells us if a range is a subset of another one, but 'well within' inside it, i.e. subject to an epsilon. Note that this cannot just operate on Comparable; it has to deal with things that can be converted to a number, because otherwise it doesn't make sense to add/subtract an epsilon. So this only works with RBNumeric.

    • getMinMaxOfClosedRanges

      public static <C extends java.lang.Comparable<? super C>> ClosedRange<C> getMinMaxOfClosedRanges​(java.util.Iterator<ClosedRange<C>> iterator)
      Returns a closed range for this collection of ranges where the lower endpoint is the min of all endpoints, end the upper endpoint is the max of all endpoints. It's not called something like 'rangeSetUnion', because there could be gaps; e.g. [1, 3] and [10, 13] will return [1, 13] here, even though there's a gap between 3 and 10. All ranges passed in must be closed ranges. Throws if the iterator is empty.

    • getMinMaxOfClosedRanges

      @SafeVarargs public static <C extends java.lang.Comparable<? super C>> ClosedRange<C> getMinMaxOfClosedRanges​(ClosedRange<C> first, ClosedRange<C>... rest)
      Returns a closed range for this collection of ranges where the lower endpoint is the min of all endpoints, end the upper endpoint is the max of all endpoints. It's not called something like 'rangeSetUnion', because there could be gaps; e.g. [1, 3] and [10, 13] will return [1, 13] here, even though there's a gap between 3 and 10. All ranges passed in must be closed ranges. Throws if the iterator is empty.

    • withNewLowerEndpointFloor

      public static <C extends java.lang.Comparable<? super C>> com.google.common.collect.Range<C> withNewLowerEndpointFloor​(com.google.common.collect.Range<C> range, C newLowerBoundFloor)
      Returns a copy of the input range, with the lower bound possibly replaced. If the input range has no lower bound, the returned range will have the supplied lower bound (as a closed bound). If a lower bound is present, the greater of the existing and the supplied lower bound will be used. This functionality could be (almost) implemented with withNewLowerEndpoint(). The only difference here is the treatment of the lower bound type; this forces it to be 'closed' if it is overriden by the supplied value. This is a bit inelegant and may be confusing, but we actually want it to be that way.
      See Also:
      withNewLowerEndpoint(com.google.common.collect.Range<P>, java.util.function.Function<java.util.Optional<P>, P>)

    • withNewUpperEndpointCeiling

      public static <C extends java.lang.Comparable<? super C>> com.google.common.collect.Range<C> withNewUpperEndpointCeiling​(com.google.common.collect.Range<C> range, C newUpperBoundCeiling)
      Returns a copy of the input range, with the upper bound possibly replaced. If the input range has no upper bound, the returned range will have the supplied upper bound (as a closed bound). If an upper bound is present, the lesser (i.e. tighter) of the existing and the supplied upper bound will be used.

    • withNewDecreasedClosedLowerEndpoint

      public static <P extends java.lang.Comparable<? super P>> com.google.common.collect.Range<P> withNewDecreasedClosedLowerEndpoint​(com.google.common.collect.Range<P> startingRange, java.util.function.UnaryOperator<P> existingToNewLowerEndpointCalculator)
      Creates a copy of a range with a new lower endpoint that must be lower than the existing one. The new lower bound type will be CLOSED, regardless of the bound type of the original.

      If the initial range has an open lower bound and is extended down to that same bound, this will also count as "decreased". E.g. extending (3, 5] to [3, 5] is supported.

    • minimallyLoosenRangeToTouchOtherRange

      public static <P extends java.lang.Comparable<? super P>> com.google.common.collect.Range<P> minimallyLoosenRangeToTouchOtherRange​(com.google.common.collect.Range<P> initialRange, com.google.common.collect.Range<P> otherRange)
      Loosen a Range just enough to intersect another range by a single point.

      For example, [3.0, 5.0] would be loosened to [3.0, 7.0] to mininally overlap with [7.0, 9.0].

      Note that if the initial range is loosened, the bound type on the loosened side will be CLOSED. E.g. [3.0, 5.0) would be loosened to [3.0, 7.0] to minimally overlap with [7.0, 10.0].

      Note that Guava defines (3.0, 5.0) to intersect with (5.0, 9.0), even though the intersection range (5.0, 5.0) is empty.

      This means that [3.0, 5.0) will be loosened to [3.0, 7.0] to overlap with (7.0, 9.0), even though the extended range doesn't "overlap" the other range in the usual sense. However, they would "connect" according to Guava's definition.

    • toRangeWithoutTrivialEndpoints

      public static <P extends java.lang.Comparable<? super P>> com.google.common.collect.Range<P> toRangeWithoutTrivialEndpoints​(ClosedRange<P> inputRange, ClosedRange<P> widestPossibleRange)
      Converts a ClosedRange into a range that's possibly open on one or both sides, if the semantics of that ClosedRange are such that there's always some trivial bounds on each side. This is useful e.g. with ClosedUnitFractionRange, where a lower bound of UNIT_FRACTION_0 is equivalent to having no lower bound (since UnitFraction can't be below 0), and an upper bound of UNIT_FRACTION_1 is equivalent to having no upper bound. This method lets us convert e.g. a ClosedRange of [ unitFraction(0.3), UNIT_FRACTION_1 ] to a Range of [ unitFraction(0.3), +inf). This does not do any epsilon checks; e.g. [ unitFraction(0.3), unitFraction(1 - epsilon)] won't get converted to Range of [ unitFraction(0.3), +inf).
